%I A396979 #5 Jun 12 2026 09:23:05
%S A396979 1,1,1,4,48,3290,2256810
%N A396979 Number of unlabeled minimally 10-rigid graphs on n vertices.
%C A396979 A graph G is d-rigid, if every generic realization p in dimension d yields a framework (G,p) that is infinitesimally d-rigid; i.e., all its infinitesimal flexes are trivial. It is minimally d-rigid if it is d-rigid but looses this property upon deletion of any edge.
%C A396979 Every minimally 10-rigid graph with n>10 is (10,55)-sparse, that is every subgraph with n'>=10 vertices spans at most 10n'-55 edges. Minimally 10-rigid graphs have 10n-55 edges and hence are (10,55)-tight but not every (10,55)-tight graph is minimally 10-rigid.
%H A396979 Matteo Gallet, Georg Grasegger, Matthias Himmelmann and Jan Legerský, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3815171">PyRigi -- a general-purpose Python package for the rigidity and flexibility of bar-and-joint frameworks</a>, ACM Transactions on Mathematical Software, 2026.
%H A396979 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18548603">Dataset of minimally d-rigid graphs</a>, 2026.
%H A396979 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7457820">RigiComp - A Mathematica package for computational rigidity of graphs</a>, 2022.
%H A396979 PyRigi Developers, <a href="https://pyrigi.github.io/PyRigi/math/rigidity.html">Rigidity Theory</a>, 2025.
%H A396979 Walter Whiteley, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/conm/197">Some matroids from discrete applied geometry</a>, 1996.
%e A396979 The complete graphs on ten and eleven vertices are minimally 10-rigid. So is the complete graph on twelve vertices with one edge removed. The three graphs that can be obtained from the previous one by adding a new vertex and connecting it to 10 of the existing vertices, are also minimally 10-rigid.
